</Text-field><Pagebreak/><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Organizational Structure in Maple</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Description of Organizational Hierarchy</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The largest organizational unit in Maple is the Worksheet.  When you save your work in Maple, the file extension ".mws" stands for "Maple WorkSheet."</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Within a worksheet, Maple allows you to provide structure to your work through the use of Sections (and Subsections).  For example, right now the text you are reading is in the section "Organizational Structure in Maple" and under the subsection "Description of Organizational Hierarchy."  The grey boxes to the left of the section headings can be clicked to collapse and expand the corresponding sections.  The extent of a section is delimited by its "range" (a vertical line with a horizontal tail) to the left of this paragraph.</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Creating an Organizational Hierarchy</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">A Worksheet is created by File-&gt;New. </Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">The Worksheet is named by File-&gt;Save As.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To create the first Section in a worksheet, Insert-&gt;Section.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Anytime a new Section has been created, you should type in its heading and press [Enter].</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To highlight a Section, click the range indicator (the vertical line on the left) for that Section.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To create a new Section within an existing Section, highlight the existing Section and Insert-&gt;Subsection.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To create a new Section at the end of an existing Section, highlight the existing Section and Insert-&gt;Section. </Text-field></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Functional Structure in Maple</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Description of Functionality in Maple</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The fundamental building block of functionality in Maple is called a Paragraph..  Although Paragraphs can be comprised of Text, Standard Math, Maple Input, Standard Math Input, and any combination thereof,  we will limit ourselves to paragraphs that contain only Text or only Maple Input.  Adventurous students may investigate more complicated scenarios at their own risk.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Text Paragraphs are used in places where you want to speak English.  They allow you to provide notes, comments, descriptions, explanations, or any other collections of words that would help you (or your grader) to understand what is going on in the worksheet.  Text Paragraphs use black Times New Roman 12pt font by default.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple Input Paragraphs are used in places where you want to speak Maple.  They allow you to issue the commands that Maple will carry out for you.  Maple Input Paragraphs begin with a command prompt ("&gt;"), and they are always located within an Execution Group (described in the next paragraph).  Maple Input Paragraphs use red Courier New 12pt font by default.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Execution Groups contain one or more Maple Input Paragraphs as well as any related Text Paragaphs.  When you press [Enter] while the cursor is in a Maple Input Paragraph, all of the Maple Commands within the Execution Group are executed, sequentially, and any corresponding output is placed by Maple at the end of the Execution Group.  The range of an execution group is delimited by a square bracket to the left.  For example:</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">This is a Text Paragraph, within an Execution Group, in the Subsection "Description of Functionality in Maple," of the Section "Functionality in Maple."  The line that follows is a Maple Input Paragraph with a sample Maple command.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">a:=0;</Font></Text-field></Input></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Creating Functionality with Maple</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To create an Execution Group, Insert-&gt;ExecutionGroup and choose a location.
(By default, new execution groups will contain a Maple Input Paragraph.)</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To change an empty Maple Input Paragraph to an empty Text Paragraph, Insert-&gt;Text.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To create a new Paragraph, Insert-&gt;Paragraph and choose a location.
(By default, new Paragraphs are Text Paragraphs)</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To change an empty Text Paragraph to an empty Maple Input Paragraph, Insert-&gt;MapleInput.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To delete a paragraph, click Edit-&gt;DeleteParagraph or type [Ctrl]+[Delete] while the cursor is in the paragraph.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">To delete an Execution Group, select all its contents and press [Delete].</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">The Shady [Enter] Key</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The [Enter] key acts in a variety of ways under different circumstances.  If you press [Enter] while the cursor is in a Text Paragraph, a new Paragraph is created on the next line (Text by default).  If you press [Enter] while the cursor is in a Maple Input Paragraph, all of the Maple commands in the current Execution Group are executed.  If you press [Shift]+[Enter], the cursor will skip to a new line, but you will still be in the same paragraph.  This can conceivably be used to help make a paragraph more readable in some circumstances.</Text-field></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Basic Maple Operation</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">General Syntax</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Basic interaction with Maple begins when you enter a command statement.  Maple responds to your commands by performing any operations or functions requested and then displaying its interpretation of that result.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Every command must end with a either a colon or a semi-colon.  If a command ends with a semi-colon, the result is displayed.  If a line ends with a colon, no result is displayed.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">All commands and variables are case sensitive (i.e. capitalization is important)</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Some strings of characters, such as D and Pi are "protected."  This means that Maple has reserved them to name functions or special variables.  In this case, a different name should be used.</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Basic Displays</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The simplest Maple commands are statements.  In this case, Maple displays its interpretation of what you typed.  Generally there will be a close correspondence.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">See how Maple interprets some simple stuff</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">5; Gamma; gamma; PollyWannaCracker;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIiY=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlJkdhbW1hRw==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlJmdhbW1hRw==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlMlBvbGx5V2FubmFDcmFja2VyRw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Basic Operators</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple can be made more useful by using commands that contain operators.  In this case, Maple performs whatever operations it can and displays the resulting expression.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">See how Maple interprets some expressions</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">5+5; Gamma+5; gamma^2; 3!; 2/3;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIzU=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMsJiUmR2FtbWFHIiIiIiImRiU=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMqJCklJmdhbW1hRyIiIyIiIg==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIic=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMjIiIjIiIk</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Basic Functions</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Additional functionality is unleashed (that's right, unleashed) when your commands contain functions.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The sqrt function returns the square root of its argument</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">sqrt(2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMiIiMiIiI=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The evalf function returns a floating point representation of its argument</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">evalf(sqrt(2));</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMkIitpTkA5OSEiKg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The exp function returns an exponential</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">exp(4);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMtJSRleHBHNiMiIiU=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Trigonometric Functions</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple even has trigonometric functions (cos, sin, tan) and inverse trig functions (arcsin, arccos, arctan).  The bad news is that all angles are given in radians (and inverse trig functions return values in radians).  The good news is that you don't have to type in the value of <Equation input-equation="Pi;" style="2D Comment">NiMlI1BpRw==</Equation> because Maple already knows it.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Everyone knows these values by heart, but at least we see how to deal with the degrees vs. radians issue.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">cos(Pi); cos(180*(Pi/180));
arcsin(1); arcsin(1)*(180/Pi);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMhIiI=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMhIiI=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMsJCUjUGlHIyIiIiIiIw==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIyEq</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Simplifying</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple tends to automatically simplify expressions.  Sometimes it needs to be coaxed a little with the simplify command.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B+2*(A+B)^2;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMsJiUiQkciIiIqJiIiI0YlKSwmJSJBR0YlRiRGJUYnRiVGJQ==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">simplify(B+2*(A+B)^2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMsKiUiQkciIiIqJiIiI0YlKSUiQUdGJ0YlRiUqKCIiJUYlRilGJUYkRiVGJSomRidGJSlGJEYnRiVGJQ==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Assigning Variables</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Up to now all operations have not depended on previous results..  In order to make references to previous results, those results must be stored.  Storage is accomplished with the := operator. </Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Assign an expression to gamma</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Gamma:=sqrt((2*A+3*B)/C);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSZHYW1tYUcqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMqJiwmJSJBRyIiIyomIiIkIiIiJSJCR0YvRi9GLyUiQ0chIiJGLw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Displaying Variables</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">To display the content of a variable, just give its name.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Gamma;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMqJiwmJSJBRyIiIyomIiIkIiIiJSJCR0YtRi1GLSUiQ0chIiJGLQ==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">You may prefer to display the name along with the content</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">'Gamma'=Gamma;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSZHYW1tYUcqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMqJiwmJSJBRyIiIyomIiIkIiIiJSJCR0YvRi9GLyUiQ0chIiJGLw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Using Variables</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Whenever you type a name that has been assigned an expression, Maple will behave as though you typed the entire expression.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">1-Gamma;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMsJiIiIkYkKiQtJSVzcXJ0RzYjKiYsJiUiQUciIiMqJiIiJEYkJSJCR0YkRiRGJCUiQ0chIiJGJEYx</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Inheritance in Variables</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">When you assign an expression to a name, other expressions that use that name inherit the expression</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A:=2*x*y*z;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJBRywkKiglInhHIiIiJSJ5R0YoJSJ6R0YoIiIj</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Gamma;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMqJiwmKiglInhHIiIiJSJ5R0YrJSJ6R0YrIiIlKiYiIiRGKyUiQkdGK0YrRislIkNHISIiRis=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Remember Your Colon</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">When you forget to put a colon before the equal sign, the resulting equation is echoed, but nothing is assigned.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Time=420;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSVUaW1lRyIkPyU=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Time;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlJVRpbWVH</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Time:=420;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSVUaW1lRyIkPyU=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Time;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiJD8l</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Clearing Variables</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">To clear a variable, reassign the variable to its own name in single quotes.  The restart command clears the values of all variables.  It is a good idea to place a restart command at the beginning of any new task (for example, the start of each problem).  No result is displayed for restart.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Set A to five, B to six, and C to seven (without displaying the output).</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A:=5: B:=6: C:=7:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Display A, B and C.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A; B; C;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIiY=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIic=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIig=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Clear B and display A, B and C.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B:='B': A; B; C;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIiY=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlIkJH</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiIig=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Clear all variables and display A, B and C.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">restart; A; B; C;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlIkFH</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlIkJH</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMlIkNH</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Tools for Solving Systems of Linear Equations</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Loading the Linear Algebra Library</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Many specialized commands are not loaded by default when Maple is open.  These commands are grouped into groups known as libraries.  The <Font bold="false" family="Times New Roman" foreground="[0,0,0]" size="12" style="_cstyle257" underline="false">with</Font> command is used to load a library.  The linear algebra commands in Maple are stored in the <Font bold="false" family="Times New Roman" foreground="[0,0,0]" size="12" style="_cstyle256" underline="false">linalg</Font> library.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">restart: with(linalg):</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Warning" style="Warning">Warning, the protected names norm and trace have been redefined and unprotected
</Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Linear algebra commands will need to be used in nearly all IEA problems</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Creating Matrices</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">To create a matrix variable, use the matrix function.  The matrix is given as a list of rows.  Each row, in turn, is a list of matrix elements, from left to right.  Lists in Maple are enclosed by square brackets and separated by commas.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define each row as a list of elements, then the matrix as a list of rows. (Note that [Shift]+[Enter] is used between each command to make the definition process easier to read and comprehend)</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">row1:=[0,1,3]:
row2:=[2,4,0]:
row3:=[4,8,1]:
A:=matrix([row1,row2,row3]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJBRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzclNyUiIiEiIiIiIiQ3JSIiIyIiJUYqNyVGLyIiKUYr</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">A vector is a special case of a matrix.  Vectors have only one column.  They can be constructed with the vector command</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define a vector </Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">v:=vector([-3,0,3]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJ2Ry0lJ3ZlY3Rvckc2IzclISIkIiIhIiIk</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Note that, although Maple appears to display the elements of the vector horizontally, they are separated by commas, indicating that each element is a separate row.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs"/><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Matrices can also be created from existing matrices.  One good example is augmented matrices, which are constructed with the augment command</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Create an augmented matrix from A and v</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A_AugmentedBy_v:=augment(A,v);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JTBBX0F1Z21lbnRlZEJ5X3ZHLSUnbWF0cml4RzYjNyU3JiIiISIiIiIiJCEiJDcmIiIjIiIlRipGKjcmRjAiIilGK0Ys</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Evaluating a Matrix</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Matrices are often defined in terms of other matrices.  In these cases, the new matrix is defined only in terms of the names of the matrices to which its definition refers.  The actual elements of the new matrix are not defined until the evalm function is applied.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define A4 in terms of A</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A4:=3*A;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNBNEcsJCUiQUciIiQ=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define all elements of A4 in terms of the elements of A</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A4:=evalm(3*A);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNBNEctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIhIiIkIiIqNyUiIiciIzdGKjclRi8iI0NGKw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Calculating the Determinant of a Matrix</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple makes determinant calculations easy for you with the det command</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the determinant of matrix A</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">det(A);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMhIiM=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Finding the Inverse of a Matrix</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple makes it easy to find the inverse of a matrix with the inverse command.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Find the inverse of A</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A_inverted:=inverse(A);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JStBX2ludmVydGVkRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzclNyUhIiMjISNCIiIjIiInNyUiIiJGLiEiJDclIiIhRipGMA==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Note that if the matrix cannot be inverted (because it is singular), an error message will tell you so.</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Multiplying Matrices</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple makes it easy to multiply two matrices with the multiply command</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Multiply A by its inverse.  The results should be the identity matrix.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">ShouldBeIdentity:=multiply(A,A_inverted);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JTFTaG91bGRCZUlkZW50aXR5Ry0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzclNyUiIiIiIiFGKzclRitGKkYrNyVGK0YrRio=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Elementary Row Operations</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">There are three fundamental operations commonly performed on a matrix in solving equations; swapping two rows, multiplying a row by a constant, and adding rows to each other.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The command below swaps rows 1 and 2.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A1:=swaprow(A, 1, 2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNBMUctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIjIiIlIiIhNyVGLCIiIiIiJDclRisiIilGLg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The command below multiplues row 1 by 1/2.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A2:=mulrow(A1, 1, 1/2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNBMkctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIiIiIjIiIhNyVGLEYqIiIkNyUiIiUiIilGKg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The command below adds row 1, multiplied by -4, to row 3.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">A3:=addrow(A2, 1, 3, -4);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNBM0ctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIiIiIjIiIhNyVGLEYqIiIkNyVGLEYsRio=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">These three operations can be used to perform Gauss-Jordan Elimination on an augmented matrix, after which the solution for the corresponding system of equations can be determined by inspection.</Text-field></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Methods for Solving Systems of Linear Equations</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Gauss-Jordan Elimination</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">We will illustrate the use of Gauss-Jordan Elimination in solving the system of equations</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="x+2*y = 3;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCYlInhHIiIiKiYiIiNGJiUieUdGJkYmIiIk</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="x-y = -3;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCYlInhHIiIiJSJ5RyEiIiwkIiIkRig=</Equation></Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define the coeffecient matrix and right-hand side vector by inspection of equations</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B_coeff:=matrix(2,2, [1,2, 1,-1]);
B_rhs:=vector([3,-3]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JShCX2NvZWZmRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzckNyQiIiIiIiM3JEYqISIi</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSZCX3Joc0ctJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JCIiJCEiJA==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Augment the coefficient matrix by the right-hand side vector</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B:=augment(B_coeff, B_rhs);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJCRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzckNyUiIiIiIiMiIiQ3JUYqISIiISIk</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Use elementary row operations to reach reduced row echelon form</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B1:=addrow(B, 1, 2, -1);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNCMUctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JDclIiIiIiIjIiIkNyUiIiEhIiQhIic=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B2:=mulrow(B1, 2, -1/3);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNCMkctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JDclIiIiIiIjIiIkNyUiIiFGKkYr</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">B3:=addrow(B2, 2, 1, -2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNCM0ctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JDclIiIiIiIhISIiNyVGK0YqIiIj</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Reading the solution from the matrix, <Equation input-equation="x = -1;" style="2D Comment">NiMvJSJ4RywkIiIiISIi</Equation> and <Equation input-equation="y = 2;" style="2D Comment">NiMvJSJ5RyIiIw==</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The augmented matrix could also have been brought to reduced row echelon form by either of the single commands rref or gaussjord.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Use rref to convert B to reduced row echelon form</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">rref(B);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMtJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JDclIiIiIiIhISIiNyVGKUYoIiIj</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Use gaussjord to convert B to reduced row echelon form</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">gaussjord(B);eq</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMtJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JDclIiIiIiIhISIiNyVGKUYoIiIj</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Cramer's Rule</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Here we will use the Cramer's Rule algorithm to solve the system</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="2*x+3*y-z = 1;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCgqJiIiIyIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiRGJyUieUdGJ0YnJSJ6RyEiIkYn</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="3*x+5*y+2*z = 8;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCgqJiIiJCIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiZGJyUieUdGJ0YnKiYiIiNGJyUiekdGJ0YnIiIp</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="x-2*y-3*z = -1;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCglInhHIiIiKiYiIiNGJiUieUdGJiEiIiomIiIkRiYlInpHRiZGKiwkRiZGKg==</Equation></Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Form the 4 matrices used in the algorithm</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">d1:=[ 2, 3,-1]: x1:=[ 1, 3,-1]: y1:=[ 2, 1,-1]: z1:=[ 2, 3, 1]: 
d2:=[ 3, 5, 2]: x2:=[ 8, 5, 2]: y2:=[ 3, 8, 2]: z2:=[ 3, 5, 8]: 
d3:=[ 1,-2,-3]: x3:=[-1,-2,-3]: y3:=[ 1,-1,-3]: z3:=[ 1,-2,-1]: 
D_coeff:=matrix([d1,d2,d3]);
Nx:=matrix([x1,x2,x3]);
Ny:=matrix([y1,y2,y3]);
Nz:=matrix([z1,z2,z3]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JShEX2NvZWZmRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzclNyUiIiMiIiQhIiI3JUYrIiImRio3JSIiIiEiIyEiJA==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNOeEctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIiIiIkISIiNyUiIikiIiYiIiM3JUYsISIjISIk</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNOeUctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIjIiIiISIiNyUiIiQiIilGKjclRitGLCEiJA==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNOekctJSdtYXRyaXhHNiM3JTclIiIjIiIkIiIiNyVGKyIiJiIiKTclRiwhIiMhIiI=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Now the determinants of the matrices are used to calculate the solution</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">x=det(Nx)/det(D_coeff); y=det(Ny)/det(D_coeff); z=det(Nz)/det(D_coeff);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ4RyIiJA==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ5RyEiIg==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ6RyIiIw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Matrix Inversion</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">We will use matrix inversion to solve the system of equations</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="7*x+4*y-2*z+4*w = 8;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiKCIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiVGJyUieUdGJ0YnKiYiIiNGJyUiekdGJyEiIiomRipGJyUid0dGJ0YnIiIp</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="2*x-3*y+7*z-6*w = 4;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiIyIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiRGJyUieUdGJyEiIiomIiIoRiclInpHRidGJyomIiInRiclIndHRidGLCIiJQ==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="5*x+6*y+2*z-5*w = 2;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiJiIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIidGJyUieUdGJ0YnKiYiIiNGJyUiekdGJ0YnKiZGJkYnJSJ3R0YnISIiRi0=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="3*x+3*y-5*z+8*w = 9;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiJCIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiZGJkYnJSJ5R0YnRicqJiIiJkYnJSJ6R0YnISIiKiYiIilGJyUid0dGJ0YnIiIq</Equation></Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define the coefficient matrix</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">row1:=[7, 4,-2, 4]:
row2:=[2,-3, 7,-6]:
row3:=[5, 6, 2,-5]:
row4:=[3, 3,-5, 8]:
A:=matrix([row1,row2,row3,row4]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJBRy0lJ21hdHJpeEc2IzcmNyYiIigiIiUhIiNGKzcmIiIjISIkRiohIic3JiIiJiIiJ0YuISImNyYiIiRGNkY0IiIp</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define the vector of rhs.</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">v:=vector([8,4,2,9]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSJ2Ry0lJ3ZlY3Rvckc2IzcmIiIpIiIlIiIjIiIq</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Solution vector to the set of equations can be found by multiplying the coefficient matrix by the vector of rhs</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">multiply(inverse(A), v);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMtJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JiMhI0giI0cjIiNAIiIpIyIkJkgiI2MjIiQyIkYp</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Solve Command</Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">restart;</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">We will illustrate the use of the solve command for the same system of equations used for matrix inversion</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="7*x+4*y-2*z+4*w = 8;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiKCIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiVGJyUieUdGJ0YnKiYiIiNGJyUiekdGJyEiIiomRipGJyUid0dGJ0YnIiIp</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="2*x-3*y+7*z-6*w = 4;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiIyIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIiRGJyUieUdGJyEiIiomIiIoRiclInpHRidGJyomIiInRiclIndHRidGLCIiJQ==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="5*x+6*y+2*z-5*w = 2;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiJiIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiYiIidGJyUieUdGJ0YnKiYiIiNGJyUiekdGJ0YnKiZGJkYnJSJ3R0YnISIiRi0=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="2D Comment"><Equation input-equation="3*x+3*y-5*z+8*w = 9;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLCoqJiIiJCIiIiUieEdGJ0YnKiZGJkYnJSJ5R0YnRicqJiIiJkYnJSJ6R0YnISIiKiYiIilGJyUid0dGJ0YnIiIq</Equation></Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define the equations.  If equations are going to be used in the solve command it is important that they are formatted correctly.  The following syntax should be used:</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="_cstyle258"><Font bold="false" family="Times New Roman" foreground="[0,0,0]" size="12" underline="false">var_name:= lhs = rhs</Font></Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">eq1:=7*x+4*y-2*z+4*w=8;
eq2:=2*x-3*y+7*z-6*w=4;
eq3:=5*x+6*y+2*z-5*w=2;
eq4:=3*x+3*y-5*z+8*w=9;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSRlcTFHLywqJSJ4RyIiKComIiIlIiIiJSJ5R0YrRisqJiIiI0YrJSJ6R0YrISIiKiZGKkYrJSJ3R0YrRisiIik=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSRlcTJHLywqJSJ4RyIiIyomIiIkIiIiJSJ5R0YrISIiKiYiIihGKyUiekdGK0YrKiYiIidGKyUid0dGK0YtIiIl</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSRlcTNHLywqJSJ4RyIiJiomIiInIiIiJSJ5R0YrRisqJiIiI0YrJSJ6R0YrRisqJkYoRislIndHRishIiJGLg==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSRlcTRHLywqJSJ4RyIiJComRigiIiIlInlHRipGKiomIiImRiolInpHRiohIiIqJiIiKUYqJSJ3R0YqRioiIio=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The solve command has two components to its syntax: a set of equations, and a set of variables to solve for.  In Maple, a set of variables is enclosed in curly brackets {}..  Note that this will not assign the solution values to the variables..</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">solve({eq1, eq2, eq3, eq4}, {w, x, y, z});
'w'=w;'x'=x;'y'=y;'z'=z;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM8Ji8lIndHIyIkMiIiI0cvJSJ4RyMhI0hGKC8lInpHIyIkJkgiI2MvJSJ5RyMiI0AiIik=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ3R0Yk</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ4R0Yk</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ5R0Yk</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ6R0Yk</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The solution values can be assigned to the variables by using the assign command</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">assign(solve({eq1, eq2, eq3, eq4}, {w, x, y, z}));
'w'=w;'x'=x;'y'=y;'z'=z;</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ3RyMiJDIiIiNH</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ4RyMhI0giI0c=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ5RyMiI0AiIik=</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMvJSJ6RyMiJCZIIiNj</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Vector Operations</Text-field></Title><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Creating Vectors</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">As discussed when introducing matrices, vectors are just a specific type of matrix in which each row has only one element (that is, the matrix has only one column).  Maple provides a special function (called vector) to create these special matrices.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Generate vectors v1 and v2</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">V1:=vector([1,2,3]);
V2:=vector([4,5,6]);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNWMUctJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JSIiIiIiIyIiJA==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNWMkctJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JSIiJSIiJiIiJw==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Accessing Vector Elements</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The elements of a vector can be accessed by their index.  Indices are addressed in square brackets, following the vector name</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Extract the elements of V2</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">Element1OfV2:=V2[1];
Element2OfV2:=V2[2];
Element3OfV2:=V2[3];</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS1FbGVtZW50MU9mVjJHIiIl</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS1FbGVtZW50Mk9mVjJHIiIm</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS1FbGVtZW50M09mVjJHIiIn</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Evaluating a Vector</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Vectors are often defined in terms of other vectors.  In these cases, the new vector is defined only in terms of the names of the vectors to which its definition refers.  The actual elements of the new vector are not defined until the evalm function is applied.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define V3 in terms of V1 and V2</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">V3:=V1+5*V2; Element1OfV3:=V3[1];</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNWM0csJiUjVjFHIiIiKiYiIiZGJyUjVjJHRidGJw==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS1FbGVtZW50MU9mVjNHJiwmJSNWMUciIiIqJiIiJkYoJSNWMkdGKEYoNiNGKA==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Define all elements of V3 in terms of the elements of V1 and V2</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">V3:=evalm(V1+5*V2); Element1OfV3:=V3[1];</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSNWM0ctJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JSIjQCIjRiIjTA==</Equation></Text-field><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS1FbGVtZW50MU9mVjNHIiNA</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Dot Products</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple has a function to calculate the dot product called dotprod</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the dot product of V1 and V2</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">&#12;dotprod(V1,V2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMiI0s=</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Some interpretations that can come in handy (for example, while doing your homework)</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">The dot product's value is given by  <Equation input-equation="A.B = abs(A)*abs(B)*cos(theta);" style="2D Comment">NiMvLSUiLkc2JCUiQUclIkJHKigtJSRhYnNHNiNGJyIiIi1GKzYjRihGLS0lJGNvc0c2IyUmdGhldGFHRi0=</Equation> , where <Equation input-equation="theta;" style="2D Comment">NiMlJnRoZXRhRw==</Equation> is the angle between the vectors.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Since <Equation input-equation="abs(A)*abs(B)*cos(theta) = abs(B)*abs(A)*cos(theta);" style="2D Comment">NiMvKigtJSRhYnNHNiMlIkFHIiIiLUYmNiMlIkJHRiktJSRjb3NHNiMlJnRoZXRhR0YpKihGKkYpRiVGKUYtRik=</Equation>, it must follow that <Equation input-equation="A.B = B.A;" style="2D Comment">NiMvLSUiLkc2JCUiQUclIkJHLUYlNiRGKEYn</Equation>  (i.e. order is unimportant in dot products).</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Using simple trigonometry, you (yes, you) can show that <Equation input-equation="abs(A)*cos(theta);" style="2D Comment">NiMqJi0lJGFic0c2IyUiQUciIiItJSRjb3NHNiMlJnRoZXRhR0Yo</Equation> is the projection of <Equation input-equation="A;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkFH</Equation> along the direction of <Equation input-equation="B;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkJH</Equation> (also known as the component of <Equation input-equation="A;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkFH</Equation> along the direction of <Equation input-equation="B;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkJH</Equation>.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Using simple trigonometry, (or arguing that order is unimportant in dot products) you can show that <Equation input-equation="abs(B)*cos(theta);" style="2D Comment">NiMqJi0lJGFic0c2IyUiQkciIiItJSRjb3NHNiMlJnRoZXRhR0Yo</Equation> is the projection of <Equation input-equation="B;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkJH</Equation> along the direction of <Equation input-equation="A;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkFH</Equation> (also known as the component of <Equation input-equation="B;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkJH</Equation> along the direction of <Equation input-equation="A;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIkFH</Equation>.</Text-field><Text-field layout="Bullet Item" style="Bullet Item">Using the previous two statements, you can show that the dot product between any vector <Equation input-equation="V;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIlZH</Equation> and any unit vector <Equation input-equation="n;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIm5H</Equation> is the component of <Equation input-equation="V;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIlZH</Equation> along the direction of <Equation input-equation="n;" style="2D Comment">NiMlIm5H</Equation>.</Text-field></Section><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Magnitude of a Vector</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">There are several ways to determine a vector's magnitude in Maple</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the magnitude of V1 using the norm command (of type "frobenius")</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">MagnitudeOfV1:=norm(V1,frobenius);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS5NYWduaXR1ZGVPZlYxRyokLSUlc3FydEc2IyIjOSIiIg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the magnitude of V1 by taking the root of the sum of the element squares</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">MagnitudeOfV1:=sqrt(V1[1]^2+V1[2]^2+V1[3]^2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS5NYWduaXR1ZGVPZlYxRyokLSUlc3FydEc2IyIjOSIiIg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the magnitude of V1 by taking the root of the dot product of V1 with itself (to see why this works, see the note at the end of the section on dot products, and bear in mind that the angle between V1 and V1 is zero)</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">MagnitudeOfV1:=sqrt(dotprod(V1,V1));</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JS5NYWduaXR1ZGVPZlYxRyokLSUlc3FydEc2IyIjOSIiIg==</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">The magnitude of a vector comes into play when calculating collinear unit vectors.  Vector magnitudes also play a key role in the interpretation of dot products included in the "Dot Products" section.</Text-field></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Unit Vectors</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">A unit vector in the same direction as a defined vector can be calculated by traditional means with Maple's assistance, or Maple can handle the whole task on its own.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate a unit vector by dividing a vector by its magnitude</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">unit_V1:=evalm(V1/MagnitudeOfV1);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSh1bml0X1YxRy0lJ3ZlY3Rvckc2IzclLCQqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMiIzkiIiIjRi9GLiwkRiojRi8iIigsJEYqIyIiJEYu</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Allow Maple to calculate the unit vector</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">unit_V1:=normalize(V1);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiM+JSh1bml0X1YxRy0lJ3ZlY3Rvckc2IzclLCQqJC0lJXNxcnRHNiMiIzkiIiIjRi9GLiwkRiojRi8iIigsJEYqIyIiJEYu</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2">Cross Products</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Maple has a function to calculate the cross product called crossprod</Text-field><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" style="NormalSplitParagraphs">Calculate the cross product of V1 and V2</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="NormalSplitParagraphs" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"><Font italic="false" size="12" underline="false">&#12;crossprod(V1,V2);</Font></Text-field></Input><Output><Text-field layout="Maple Output" style="2D Output"><Equation style="2D Output">NiMtJSd2ZWN0b3JHNiM3JSEiJCIiJ0Yn</Equation></Text-field></Output></Group></Section></Section><Text-field/></Worksheet>